One of the reasons I always surf over to the American Movie
Channel, besides the fact that I'm crazy about Katherine Hepburn,
Spencer Tracy, Cary Grant, Jimmy Stewart (etc., etc) movies, is to
see some of the now-antique (or at least collectible) items
shown in the films.

A couple years ago (maybe Connie S. can help out with this if
she reads this thread), AntiqueWeek did a story on a woman,
I believe in Indiana, who does a booming business selling
props to Hollywood studios. Not so much furniture and large items,
but little things like old detergent boxes and soda bottles...
everyday sorts of things that add an authentic touch.

On a related note, a few summers ago, when I was able to put
my freelance work aside for a few days, I volunteered to be
an extra in _My Summer Story_, the sequel (sort of) to that
Christmas movie about the kid who wanted a Red Ryder BB gun
for Christmas.

The scenes I was in were filmed in three grand old movie
theatres here in Cleveland, so I didn't get to see many
home interior props. But there was one funny thing. The
&quot;bit&quot; that those theatre scenes revolved around was the
free china that movie theatres used to give out to drum up
business. The premise was that this theatre was giving out
china with movie stars images on it and that it was about
the 3rd week running for gravy boats (I forget the name
of the movie idol whose face appeared on 'em).

The movie-goers were not taking it anymore, and they (we)
threw their gravy boats at the emcee on the stage. The
items we threw were actually very dense styrofoam of some
sort, painted with a pearlized-looking glaze to make
them look real.

In another scene we played &quot;Beeno,&quot; a forerunner (or copycat) of
bingo, with dried beans used as markers. I could almost imagine
I was back in the 1940s. What a hoot it was!

The extras had to show up in vintage clothing, or at least in
clothing classic enough to top off with an authentic hat or
coat to make it look real. I wore my aunt's lovely little silk-
flower-decorated straw hat that she was married in, in the
early 40s.

Sorry to get farther off the semi-off-topic thread, but this
one reminded me of one of the most fun experiences I've had.
Mary Steenbergen, btw, was delightful and looked like a
natural in the vintage dresses the costume people drummed
up for her.

Thanks for stirring up this bit of nostalgia, Rich. :)

Linda Z.

