"/> Probably because most folks had pretty much written off the movie and it had
been universally panned when it was released in 1980. Despite the weak plot, I
don't think Jane Seymour ever looked better. However, people in the audience
did giggle a lot each time when the camera held onto the dreamy look in
Christopher's eyes just about three beats too long. It was filmed here in
Michigan at the Grand Hotel on Mackinac Island and it didn't take too much
effort to make the hotel look period and elegant, as it still is. There are no
motorized vehicles allowed on the Island (Except for a well hidden fire engine
and ambulance) and you do have a real time warp feeling when you go there-
about a half hour ferry ride. There are periodic &quot;Somewhere in Time&quot; events at
the hotel that draw hundreds of people, most in costume, and our local
Victorian Society Chapter had also done a weekend program there in appropriate
outfits. There is an Antique Show there every Fall, so I guess you could write
it off as a buying trip. Start saving now as their rack rate starts about
$300/night for 2 people/ 1 bed, but that's MAP. There's also a lot of B&amp;B's but
the season is short- about May to October. If you want to just look at the
hotel up close, they now charge (I think it's about $5.00 each) to wander on
the porch and the public areas. Those people are called &quot;Fudgies&quot; as the
usually have one hand perpetually loading fudge from one of the many wharfside
stores into their mouth; probably the money just covers the removal of the
sticky fingerprints.

A little &quot;Factoid&quot;-- The film was originally scripted to be shot at equally
beautiful and elegant Hotel Del Coronado on the island of the same name off San
Diego, but there were too many problems like eliminating all the autos,
interrupting the hotel operations, etc. (Other films were done there including
&quot;Some Like It Hot&quot;) If you go there, you can see the details in a display in
one of the lower common hallways. The furnishings aren't Grand Hotel, but the
woodwork alone is worth the trip. And the whole site is a reminder of a time
when hotels were an event, not just a place to get through the night.

The last time I was there my room opened on the beautiful inner courtyard,
where at sunset there was a piano being played below; after a few classical
selections the music changed to the &quot;Somewhere in Time&quot; score.....Sadly, for at
that part of my trip, I was alone. &lt;BIG Sigh&gt; But don't feel really sorry for
me, as there was a large group of us, and, by Friday a friend from Dana Point
made the rest of the stay worthwhile.

